{{ja-kanjitab|えびす|yomi=k}}

{{IPAfont|⟨emi<sub>1</sub>si⟩}} → *{{IPAchar|/emʲisɨ/}} → {{IPAchar|/emisə/}} → {{IPAchar|/ebisu/}}

Shift from {{inh|ja|ojp|sort=えひす|蝦夷|tr={{w|Emishi}}}}, modern ''Ezo''.

{{ja-noun|えびす}}

# {{lb|ja|sort=えひす|historical}} {{synonym of|lang=ja|蝦夷|tr=Ezo|nodot=1|sort=えひす}}: an [[ancient]] [[ethnic group]] attested in the ''{{w|Nihon Shoki}}'' that once lived on what is now the {{w|Kantō region|Kantō}}, {{w|Hokuriku region|Hokuriku}} and {{w|Tōhoku region|Tōhoku regions}}, likely as far as {{w|Hokkaido}}, possibly related to the {{w|Ainu people}}; dubbed as "[[barbarian]]s" or "[[savage]]s" by the [[Yamato]]
# a [[person]] [[live|living]] [[far away]] from the {{m|ja|都|tr=miyako||[[capital]]}}, loosely translated to "[[bumpkin]]" or "[[hick]]"
#: {{syn|ja|田舎者|tr=inakamono}}
# {{lb|ja|sort=えひす|regional|derogatory}} a [[barbarian]], [[savage]], ''especially'' referring to the {{m|ja|東夷|tr=azuma-ebisu||[[warrior]] from the [[east]]ern parts of Japan}}
#* '''1204''', ''{{w|lang=ja|秋篠月清集|Akishino Gesseishū}}'' (book 1, poem 223)
#*: {{ja-usex|sort=えひす|わがおもふ人だにすまばみちのくの'''えびす'''の里もうときものかは|わが おもふ ひと だに すまば ^みちのく の '''えびす''' の さと も うとき もの か は|rom=waga omou hito dani sumaba Michinoku no '''ebisu''' no sato utoki mono ka wa}}
# {{lb|ja|sort=えひす|by extension|derogatory}} a [[foreigner]]

{{ja-kanjitab|い|yomi=o}}
{{IPAchar|/ji/}} → {{IPAchar|/i/}}

From {{bor|ja|ltc|sort=い|-}} {{ltc-l|夷}}, originally referred to one of the [[ancient]] [[tribe]]s [[east]] of [[China]].

{{ja-noun|い}}

# those [[people]] with [[differ]]ing [[language]]s and/or [[culture]]s
#: {{syn|ja|異民族|tr=iminzoku}}
# a [[barbarian]], [[savage]]; [[uncivilized]] [[people]] {{qualifier|living to the east of ancient Imperial China; included Japan}}
#: {{syn|ja|野蛮人|tr=yabanjin}}
# a [[neutral]] {{gl|[[position]]}}
#: {{syn|ja|無色|tr=mushoku}}
